@page "/quick-start"
<PageTitle>Quick Start - Saascade Docs</PageTitle>

<h1>Quick Start</h1>

<main class="documentation">

    <section class="card">

        <h2>Prerequisites</h2>

        <p class="subtitle">
            Make sure your development environment is ready before you begin.
        </p>

        <hr />

        <ul>
            <li><a href="https://dotnet.microsoft.com/download">.NET 10 SDK</a> or later.</li>
            <li>An IDE — Visual Studio 2022+, VS Code with the C# Dev Kit, or JetBrains Rider.</li>
            <li>A Blazor WebAssembly or Blazor Server project.</li>
        </ul>

    </section>

    <section class="card">

        <h2>1. Create a Blazor Project</h2>

        <p>
            If you don't have one yet, scaffold a new Blazor WebAssembly app:
        </p>

        <pre><code>dotnet new blazorwasm -o MyApp
cd MyApp</code></pre>

    </section>

    <section class="card">

        <h2>2. Install the Package</h2>

        <p>
            Add the Saascade NuGet package to your project:
        </p>

        <pre><code>dotnet add package Saascade.Blazor.Components</code></pre>

    </section>

    <section class="card">

        <h2>3. Register a Design System</h2>

        <p>
            Open <code>Program.cs</code> and register the design system you want to use.
            This example uses DaisyUI:
        </p>

        <pre><code>builder.Services.AddSingleton&lt;IDesignSystem&gt;(DesignSystems.Tailwind.DaisyUI);</code></pre>

        <p>
            You can swap to any supported design system — see the
            <a href="/design-systems">Design Systems</a> page for the full list.
        </p>

    </section>

    <section class="card">

        <h2>4. Add Imports</h2>

        <p>
            Add the following line to your <code>_Imports.razor</code> so all Saascade
            components are available in every page:
        </p>

        <pre><code>@@using Saascade.Blazor.Components</code></pre>

    </section>

    <section class="card">

        <h2>5. Add Stylesheet References</h2>

        <p>
            Each design system may require external stylesheets.
            For DaisyUI, add the Tailwind/DaisyUI CDN link in your
            <code>index.html</code> (WebAssembly) or <code>App.razor</code> (Server):
        </p>

        <pre><code>&lt;link href="https://cdn.jsdelivr.net/npm/daisyui/dist/full.min.css" rel="stylesheet" /&gt;
&lt;script src="https://cdn.tailwindcss.com"&gt;&lt;/script&gt;</code></pre>

        <p>
            For Bootstrap 5, use the Bootstrap CDN instead:
        </p>

        <pre><code>&lt;link href="https://cdn.jsdelivr.net/npm/bootstrap@@5/dist/css/bootstrap.min.css" rel="stylesheet" /&gt;</code></pre>

    </section>

    <section class="card">

        <h2>6. Use Your First Component</h2>

        <p>
            Open a page and add a Saascade component.
            Here's a simple card with a button:
        </p>

        <pre><code>&lt;Card&gt;
    &lt;CardBody&gt;
        &lt;H2&gt;Hello Saascade!&lt;/H2&gt;
        &lt;P&gt;This is your first component.&lt;/P&gt;
        &lt;Button type="Primary"&gt;Click Me&lt;/Button&gt;
    &lt;/CardBody&gt;
&lt;/Card&gt;</code></pre>

    </section>

    <section class="card">

        <h2>7. Run the App</h2>

        <p>
            Start the development server and see your component rendered
            with the chosen design system:
        </p>

        <pre><code>dotnet run</code></pre>

        <p>
            Open the URL shown in the terminal (usually <code>https://localhost:5001</code>)
            and you should see a fully styled card.
        </p>

    </section>

    <section class="card">

        <h2>Next Steps</h2>

        <p class="subtitle">
            You're up and running — here's where to go from here.
        </p>

        <hr />

        <ul>
            <li>Browse available components in the sidebar.</li>
            <li>Learn how <a href="/design-systems">Design Systems</a> work.</li>
            <li>Explore <a href="/base-components">Base Components</a> to understand the component hierarchy.</li>
            <li>Try <a href="/custom-themes">creating a custom theme</a>.</li>
        </ul>

    </section>

</main>
